### Initialize 3D Scene with Canvas Component (React JSX)

Source: https://context7.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/llms.txt

The Canvas component is the entry point for creating a 3D scene. It sets up the Three.js scene, camera, renderer, and render loop. It accepts various props for configuration, including camera settings, shadow quality, device pixel ratio, WebGL context options, and event handlers.

```jsx
import { Canvas } from '@react-three/fiber'

function App() {
  return (
    <Canvas
      camera={{ position: [0, 0, 5], fov: 75 }}
      shadows
      dpr={[1, 2]}
      gl={{ antialias: true, alpha: true }}
      frameloop="always"
      onCreated={(state) => console.log('Canvas ready', state)}
      onPointerMissed={() => console.log('Clicked outside any mesh')}
    >
      <ambientLight intensity={0.5} />
      <pointLight position={[10, 10, 10]} />
      <mesh>
        <boxGeometry args={[1, 1, 1]} />
        <meshStandardMaterial color="orange" />
      </mesh>
    </Canvas>
  )
}
```

--------------------------------

### Monitor FPS and Adjust Resolution with PerformanceMonitor

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/advanced/scaling-performance.mdx

This example demonstrates how to use the PerformanceMonitor component to dynamically adjust the device pixel ratio (dpr) based on average frames per second (fps). It triggers callbacks onIncline and onDecline to increase or decrease the dpr, aiming to maintain optimal performance. The component collects average fps over time and uses upper and lower framerate bounds to prevent rapid changes.

```jsx
function App() {
  const [dpr, setDpr] = useState(1.5)
  return (
    <Canvas dpr={dpr}>
      <PerformanceMonitor onIncline={() => setDpr(2)} onDecline={() => setDpr(1)} >

```

--------------------------------

### Enable On-Demand Rendering with frameloop='demand'

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/advanced/scaling-performance.mdx

Set the canvas `frameloop` prop to `demand` to enable on-demand rendering. This will only render frames when necessary, such as when props change, saving battery and reducing fan noise on less powerful devices.

```jsx
<Canvas frameloop="demand">

```

--------------------------------

### Avoid Object Re-creation in `useFrame` Loops

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/advanced/pitfalls.mdx

Illustrates the performance impact of creating new objects (like `THREE.Vector3`) within the `useFrame` hook, which triggers garbage collection. It shows a bad practice and a better alternative that re-uses objects.

```jsx
// ❌ Bad news for the GC
useFrame(() => {
  ref.current.position.lerp(new THREE.Vector3(x, y, z), 0.1)
})
```

```jsx
// ✅ Better re-use object
function Foo(props)
  const vec = new THREE.Vector()
  useFrame(() => {
    ref.current.position.lerp(vec.set(x, y, z), 0.1)
  })
```

--------------------------------

### Execute Code on Each Frame with useFrame

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/API/hooks.mdx

The `useFrame` hook allows you to run code on every rendered frame. It provides access to the render state and delta time. Callbacks are automatically unsubscribed when the component unmounts. Avoid calling setState within `useFrame`.

```jsx
import { useFrame } from '@react-three/fiber'

function Foo() {
  useFrame((state, delta, xrFrame) => {
    // This function runs at the native refresh rate inside of a shared render-loop
  })
}
```
